"van Beusekom J.E.E., Loebl M., Martens P.","Distant riverine nutrient supply and local temperature drive the long-term phytoplankton development in a temperate coastal basin",2009,"Journal of Sea Research","61","1-2",,"26","33",,,10.1016/j.seares.2008.06.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58149327448&partnerID=40&md5=0edad41446964f26cce07c92029500e5","Alfred-Wegener-Institute for Polar and Marine Science, Wadden Sea Station Sylt, Hafenstrasse 43, 25992 List/Sylt, Germany","van Beusekom, J.E.E., Alfred-Wegener-Institute for Polar and Marine Science, Wadden Sea Station Sylt, Hafenstrasse 43, 25992 List/Sylt, Germany; Loebl, M., Alfred-Wegener-Institute for Polar and Marine Science, Wadden Sea Station Sylt, Hafenstrasse 43, 25992 List/Sylt, Germany; Martens, P., Alfred-Wegener-Institute for Polar and Marine Science, Wadden Sea Station Sylt, Hafenstrasse 43, 25992 List/Sylt, Germany","Since 1984, salinity, temperature, phytoplankton biomass and nutrients have been monitored in the List Tidal Basin (northern Wadden Sea, Europe). Nutrient dynamics follow a clear seasonal pattern with high winter concentrations and low summer concentrations. Interannual phytoplankton dynamics in the basin apparently responded to both decreasing riverine nutrient loads and the prevailing temperature regime. The mean spring diatom biomass (as Chlorophyll a) was correlated with temperature and the highest biomass was reached after cold winters. Summer phytoplankton (May-September) gradually decreased and correlated with Total Nitrogen loads from the rivers Weser and Elbe debouching about 150 km south of the List Tidal Basin into the North Sea. During summer, the frequency of observations with low nitrate concentrations (< 0.5 μM) significantly increased. We conclude that the long-term development of the phytoplankton is driven by a combination of riverine nitrogen loads and temperature. We expect that global warming and decreasing nutrient loads will reduce the magnitude of phytoplankton blooms in the List Tidal Basin. © 2008 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Eutrophication; Long-term change; Phytoplankton; Temperature; Wadden Sea","concentration (composition); eutrophication; global warming; nitrogen; nutrient enrichment; phytoplankton; salinity; Atlantic Ocean; North Sea; Wadden Sea; algae; Bacillariophyta",,,,,,"Alpine, A.E., Cloern, J.E., Trophic interactions and direct physical effects control phytoplankton biomass and production in an estuary (1992) Limnol. Oceanogr., 37, pp. 946-955; Beukema, J.J., Cadée, G.C., Zoobenthos responses to eutrophication of the Dutch Wadden (1986) Sea. Ophelia, 26, pp. 55-64; Billén, G., Garnier, J., River basin nutrient delivery to the coastal sea: assessing its potential to sustain new production of non-siliceous algae (2007) Mar. Chem., 106, pp. 148-160; Cadée, G.C., Recurrent and changing seasonal patterns in phytoplankton of the westernmost inlet of the Dutch Wadden Sea from 1969 to 1985 (1986) Mar. Biol., 93, pp. 281-289; Cadée, G.C., Phytoplankton variability in the Marsdiep, The Netherlands (1992) ICES Mar. Sci. Symp., 195, pp. 213-222; Cadée, G.C., Hegeman, J., Primary production of phytoplankton in the Dutch Wadden Sea (1974) Neth. J. Sea Res., 3, pp. 240-259; Cadée, G.C., Hegeman, J., Seasonal and annual variation in Phaeocystis pouchetii (Haptophyceae) in the westernmost inlet of the Wadden Sea during the 1973 to 1985 period (1986) Neth. J. Sea Res., 20, pp. 29-36; Cadée, G.C., Hegeman, J., Phytoplankton in the Marsdiep at the end of the 20th century; 30 years monitoring biomass, primary production, and Phaeocystis blooms (2002) J. Sea Res., 48, pp. 97-110; Cloern, J.E., The relative importance of light and nutrient limitation of phytoplankton growth: a simple index of coastal ecosystem sensitivity to nutrient enrichment (1999) Aquat. Ecol., 33, pp. 3-16; Cloern, J.E., Dufford, R., Phytoplankton community ecology, principles applied in San Francisco Bay (2005) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser.